column1: Yes, but not updated evidence statements
Evidence Statements: This paper presented a pheochromocytoma detected by autopsy. The index case was a 26-year-old male who presented to the emergency department complaining of obstipation, severe headache and abdominal pain. The family background of the parents and siblings history is unavailable since the patient was an orphan. An autopsy revealed bilateral pheochromocytoma and acute myocardial infarction. Molecular genetic analyses for germline mutations of the VHL gene were performed after DNA extraction from normal liver tissue using standard methods. A mutation in VHL gene R167W (c.499C>T) was detected.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

column1: Yes, but not updated evidence statements
Evidence Statements: The authors studied VHL gene mutation in 31 kidney tumours from France. SSCP analysis of exon 2 and 3 and of a 450-nucleotide region in the last one third 3'-region of exon 1 of VHL gene was used to detect mutations. For tumor 3087, 2 mutations were detected. Comparison with non-tumor tissue shows that the P61P (c.183C>G) mutation in exon 1 was also present in the normal tissue, demonstrating that this is a germline mutation. This silent mutation was reported as a rare polymorphism in Sekido et al, 1994. Somatic mutation L181P (c.551T>C) in exon 3 was also detected in tumor 3087.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

column1: Yes, but not updated evidence statements
Evidence Statements: This paper analyzed VHL sequences in the renal cell carcinomas of patients exposed to high, cumulative doses of trichloroethylene. To investigate the hotspot somatic mutation, P81S (c. 241C>T) (denoted as nt454 C>T mutation in the paper), found in the tumours, germline DNA with the same mutation was used as control in the restriction enzyme AciI based assay.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

column1: Yes, but not updated evidence statements
Evidence Statements: The authors presented a cased of a 28-year-old woman with neurological symptoms from two haemangioblastomas (cerebellar and cerebro-spinal). Refined clinical work-up revealed pancreatic cysts and angiomatosis retinae. PCR/SSCP analsys and fluorescence-labelled based excision sequence scanning (F-BESS) were used to detect mutation in the VHL gene. The L140PfsX4 (c.418dup) mutation was detected in the patient. No signs of VHL disease was detected in the patient's family members (mother, brother, sister). Genetic analysis also did not reveal any VHL mutation in the family members. ACMG: 'PP4' because the patients' phenotypes are highly specific for a disease with single genetic etiology.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

column1: Yes, but not updated evidence statements
Phenotype (for reference): renal cell carcinoma; Spinal hemangioblastoma; pancrearic cysts; renal cyst
Evidence Statements: A case report describes a a 29-year-old man presenting with recurrent spinal hemangioblastomas and a negative family history for VHL. PCR/SSCP analysis with primers from the VHL gene identified a deletion of a single T nucleotide in exon 2 from the pentametic thymidines nucleotides 653-657 of exon 2 (reference transcript L15409 converted to NM_000551.3 and HGVS nomenclature: c.444del) in the patient's germline and in the tumor, but not in the DNA of his parents or sister, supporting a de novo mutation. Other family history included an aunt who died from breast cancer at age 46 and a grandfather who died of leukemia at age 56 and these are not suspected to be VHL cases. Clincal work-up also identified RCC, renal cysts, and pancreatic cysts in the proband. ACMG: PM6
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

column1: Yes, but not updated evidence statements
Phenotype (for reference): pituitary adenoma; pheochromocytoma
Evidence Statements: Thirty-nine cases of sporadic or familial pheo/PGL and pituitary adenomas (PA) were investigated. Known pheo/PGL genes (SDHA-D, SDHAF2, RET, VHL, TMEM127, MAX, FH) and pituitary adenoma genes (MEN1, AIP, CDKN1B) were sequenced using next generation or Sanger sequencing. Patient 21 with pheo/PGL and PA was found with 2 germline mutations, one in the VHL gene (c.589G>A) and one in the SDHA gene (c.91C>T). Other information is not available.

column1: Yes, but not updated evidence statements
Phenotype (for reference): pheochromocytoma
Evidence Statements: 48 patients with sporadic pheochromocytoma were reveiwed. One patient was found with bilateral pheochromocytoma and a mutation (p.Gly114Ser) in the VHL gene was found in both tumours. Germline DNA was not available for testing, but the authors conclude that the patient is 'probably germline' seeing as DNA from both tumours had the same mutation. The nucleotide change from the paper was converted to NM_000551. They had no other VHL phenoytyes and a negative family history of pheo and VHL. Family DNA was not available for genetic testing so de novo mutation cannot be confirmed. ACMG PP4

column1: Yes, but not updated evidence statements
Phenotype (for reference): Cerebellar hemangioblastoma; retinal capillary hemangioma; Pancreatic Cysts; hearing impairment
Notes: Japanese Family; 3 affected; Patient 1: Daughter; Cerebellar hemangioblastoma with obstructive hydrocephalus at 8yo; recurrent hemangioblastoma; Pancreatic Cysts; hypoacusis
Evidence Statements: A Japense family with VHL and a p.Pro86Leu familial mutation is described. Genomic DNA was isolated from 4 family members and patient 3 underwent direct sequencing of the whole gene using PCR. The mutation was then confirmed in patient 1 and 2 using restriction endonuclease anaylses. The father did not have the mutation and was asymptomatic. The variant notation from the paper was updated to NM_000551. Patient 1 (the oldest daughter) presented with symptomatic cerebellar hemangioblastoma at 8Y, which re-occurred at 15Y and 19Y. At 19Y, she also presented with retinal angioma and pancreatic cysts and hypoacusis in the left ear. Patient 2 (mother) had retinal angiomas and cerebellar hemangioblastoma at 39Y. Patient 3 (youngest daughter) underwent screening at 14Y and was found with cerebellar hemangioblastoma, retinal angiomas in the right eye, kindey cysts, pancreatic cysts, and a cystic tumor in the cervical cord. ACMG: PP4
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: 23 CNS hemangioblastoma tumor samples were studied. Blood was available for genetic analysis for 2 tumours belonging to the same patient from the University Medical Center Nijmegen, The Netherlands (tumours N379 and N380), and a germline T152P germline mutation in the VHL gene was confirmed (nucelotide reference was updated to NM_000551.) The patient was a 28Y old male with 2 cerebellar hemangioblastomas and also multiple pancreatic and epididymal cysts. Family information, including genetic testing of family members, was not described and the patient was not reported to have a postive family history of VHL. ACMG PP4

column1: Yes, but not updated evidence statements
Phenotype (for reference): hemangioblastoma; retinal capillary hemangioma
Evidence Statements: A 12Y old boy presented with symptomatic hemangioblastoma in the medulla. After surgical removal of the hemangioblastoma, he was also found with retinal capillary hemangioma of the right eye. PCR and MLPA genetic studies identified a germline VHL mutation c.208G>A in the patient. His mother and maternal aunt had a history of retinal capillary hemangioma but were not available for genetic testing. The patient was followed-up for 1 year 7 months with no complications. ACMG PP4
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

column1: Yes, but not updated evidence statements
Phenotype (for reference): cerebellar hemangioblastoma; lung adenocarcinoma; renal cell carcinoma; pancreatic cysts
Notes: Proband, Japanese; bilateral renal cell carcinoma
Evidence Statements: A case report describes a 64Y old Japanese woman with VHL and a germline mutation p.Ser65Leu in the VHL gene. She presented with cerebellar hemangioblastoma at 37Y, underwent treatment for renal cell carcinoma at 59Y and 63Y, and was also diagnosed with with pancreatic cysts, multiple hepatic adenocarcinoma and liver metastasis from the hepatic adenocarcinoma. The hepatic adenocarcinoma was found with somatic EGFR mutations and loss of heterozygosity at the VHL locus and authors speculate that dysfunctional pVHL may promote mutations on the EGFR gene. The proband has a positive family history with her older brother dying of RCC associated with VHL at 58Y and her younger sister diagnosed with RCC assoicated with VHL disease (age unknown). Genetic testing of the family members was not described. ACMG PP4
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

column1: Yes, but not updated evidence statements
Phenotype (for reference): hemangioblastoma; renal neoplasm
Notes: Germline; Multiple hemangioblastoma; kidney solid tumour
Evidence Statements: The 32-year-old male patient was admitted to Xiangya Hospital in 2006 and was found with multiple CNS hemantioblastoma of the pons, medulla oblongata, cerebellum and spinal cord. Clinical workup also identified a solid renal tumor. He was followed-up for 5 years with no other complications. The patient and his 7 family members (his parents, sister, son, sister’s son, brother, and brother’s son) were assessed by RQ-PCR assay, and no large deletions were found. Direct sequencing identified the p.Phe76del mutation in the proband and this mutation (or any other abnormality) was not found in any of the family members. All members were asymptomatic, although his father and mother did not undergo complete whole-body examination. This is supportive of a de novo mutation ACMG PM6.
Warnings: Removing redundant reference bases from variant description

Direct DNA sequencing found a c.226_228del germline mutation in the VHL gene. She had 5 siblings, 3 of which tested negative for the VHL mutation and the other 2 were not evaluated. The patient's father was tested and confirmed to be mosaic for the mutation. The father (III4) was 48Y old and found with renal cell carcinoma, brainstem and cerebellar hemangioblastoma, pancreatic cysts, and renal cysts. ACMG PP4

Evidence Statements: Two families where index patients had mosaic partents from the NIH-VHL Family Registry were reviewed. Family 1 had an index patient (III:1), a 27Y female, with hemangioblastoma found at 24Y old and pancreatic cysts. Quantitative Southern blot of germline DNA found a deletion of one entire allele of the VHL gene and direct sequencing of the other allele found no mutations. Evidence Statements: 12 cases of microcystic adenomas (serous cystadenomas) of the pancreas from the Laboratory of Pathology, National Cancer Institute, National Institutes of Health, and the New England Deaconess Hospital, Harvard Medical School were reviewed. Case 2 was a 38Y male VHL patient with a known c.481C>T germline VHL mutation (updated from legancy notation in the paper to reference NM_000551). The patient had microcystic adenoma of the pancreas, renal cell carcinoma, and pheochromocytoma. Microsatellite marker analysis demonstrated LOH at 3p25 in the microcystic adenoma. Family history was not described. ACMG PP4
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

column1: Yes, but not updated evidence statements
Phenotype (for reference): pheochromocytoma
Evidence Statements: A Chinese family with 2 VHL oatients is reported. Patient 1 is a 24Y man referred with a 3 month history of consipation and oversweat and was found with bilateral pheochromocytoma and renal cell carcinoma. Patient 2 was the younger sister of patient 1. She underwent VHL screening at 21Y and was found with pheochromocytoa. The father 55 years old did not have a significant medical history. The mother died of unknown cause at 38Y. Direct sequencing of the proband and sister identified a nonsense p.W88* germline VHL mutation. The mutation was not found in the father and testing was not available for the mother. ACMG PP4

Evidence Statements: Between 1994 and 2001, the Dutch VHL working group conducted DNA analysis on 146 probands with VHL-associated manifestations. DNA of probands was extracted from peripheral blood samples. Exons 1, 2 and 3 of the VHL gene and their flanking untranslated and intronic coding sequences were amplified by PCR and subjected to semi-automated sequence analysis. Screening for structural rearrangements, including deletions, involving the VHL gene was performed by Southern blot analysis and the multiplex ligation-dependent probe amplification (MLPA) assay. Deletions encompassing the entire VHL gene were confirmed by FISH analysis on lymphocytes from affected individuals. VHL mutations were identified in 43 families. In family 1, 6 individuals were identified as carriers of the R64P(c.191G>C) mutation in the VHL gene. Family member I-1 was diagnosed with renal cell carcinoma (RCC) at age 48 and passed away. Family member II-3 was diagnosed with bilateral pheochromocytoma at age 34. Family member III-4 was diagnosed with bilateral pheochromocytoma at age 14. Family member III-5 presented with paraganglioma and renal cyst at age 29. Family member II-1 (present age 59)and III-1 (present age 40) are asymptomatic. ACMG: 'PP1' because cosegregation with disease in multiple afffected family members in a gene definitively known to cause the disease. 'PP4' because the patients' phenotypes and family history are highly specific for a disease with single genetic etiology.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: The authors investigated the clinical characteristics and genetic profile of VHL disease in the Chinese population. 12 patients with CNS hemangioblastoma from seven Chinese families were admitted to the Department of Neurosurgery at the First Affiliated Hospital of Soochow University, between 1996 and 2010. Peripheral blood samples were obtained for genetic analysis. Direct sequencing and real-time quantitative PCR was carried out to screen for mutations in the VHL gene in the 12 patients and their 13 non-symptomatic relatives. Exon 1 deletion in VHL gene was detected in Family A and E. Proband from Family A is a male patient presented with CNS hemangioblastoma and pancreatic cyst at age 48. His son is an asymptomatic carrier. Proband from Family E is a male patient who presented with multifocal CNS hemangioblastoma at age 21. Proband's brother presented with multiple CNS hemangioblastoma at age 29. Proband's sister, nephew, niece and aunt are asymptomatic carriers. ACMG: 'PP4' because the patient's phenotype and family history are highly specific for a disease with single genetic etiology.

Evidence Statements: The authors described the growth kinetics of 96 renal tumours in 64 VHL patients. 10-ml EDTA anticoagulated blood samples were available from each patient for mutation screening of all exons of the VHL gene. Genomic DNA from blood samples was extracted using standard methods. Small deletions/insertions or point mutations were identified by DNA sequencing followed by complete mutation screening using PCR/single-strand conformation polymorphism and denaturing high-performance liquid chromatography. Germline mutation S65W(c.194C>G) was identified in Patient No. 3
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: 426 unrelated subjects with a clinical diagnosis ranging from VHL syndrome to sporadic potentially VHL-related tumours were analyzed for mutation in the VHL gene. The analysis was carried out by the VHL referral laboratory, Department of Pediatrics at the University of Padua. High-molecular-weight genomic DNA was extracted from peripheral blood leucocytes by standard protocols. Mutation scanning of the VHL gene for identification of point- or small-size mutations was conducted on the entire coding sequence and intron–exon boundaries by polymerase chain reaction (PCR) amplification, denaturating high-performance liquid chromatography (DHPLC), and direct sequence analysis. Genetic analysis was also carried out for 200 unaffected control individuals. A VHL alteration was found in 111 unrelated probands and 2 unaffected control. Mutation Y175*(c.525C>A) was identified in prodand 1. Proband 1 presented with CNS hemangioblastoma and died at age 17. ACMG: 'PP4' because the patient's phenotype is highly specific for a disease with single genetic etiology.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: 426 unrelated subjects with a clinical diagnosis ranging from VHL syndrome to sporadic potentially VHL-related tumours were analyzed for mutation in the VHL gene. Evidence Statements: 426 unrelated subjects with a clinical diagnosis ranging from VHL syndrome to sporadic potentially VHL-related tumours were analyzed for mutation in the VHL gene. Evidence Statements: This paper reports on 4 Chinese kindreds with VHL. The VHL gene was screened using direct DNA sequencing and MLPA in 44 volunteers among the 4 families. The above mutation was found in 1 kindred; 5 members were tested and 3 were found to harbour the mutation. The 2 members without a mutation were asymptomatic, while the 3 members with a mutation had manifestations. In addition to the 3 members who tested positive, there were 3 members who displayed manifestations but did not receive genetic testing. Clinical manifestations in this kindred included: CNS hemangioblastoma, pheochromocytoma, renal cell carcinoma, renal cysts, pancreatic cysts, and endolymphatic sac tumor. ACMG evidence codes: 'PP1' because of segregation results, 'PP2' because they observe a missense variant in a gene where missense variants are a common mechanism of disease, 'PP4' because the patient's phenotypes or family history are highly specific for a disease with single genetic etiology. Relevant HPO terms: Pheochromocytoma, Renal cell carcinoma, Hemangioblastoma, Multiple pancreatic cysts, Multiple renal cysts, Endolymphatic sac tumor.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: This paper reports on 4 Chinese kindreds with VHL. The VHL gene was screened using direct DNA sequencing and MLPA in 44 volunteers among the 4 families. The above mutation was found in 1 kindred; 18 members were tested and 5 were found to harbour the mutation. The 13 members without a mutation and 1 carrier were asymptomatic, while 4 of the 5 carriers had manifestations. In addition to the 4 carriers, there were 2 additional members who displayed manifestations, but died before testing could be performed. It should be noted that these family members also harboured a concurrent homozygous deletion of IRAK2. Clinical manifestations in this kindred included: CNS hemangioblastoma, pancreatic cysts, renal cell carcinoma, and pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor. ACMG evidence codes: 'PP1' because of segregation results, 'PP4' because the patient's phenotypes or family history are highly specific for a disease with single genetic etiology, 'PVS1' because they observe a single exon deletion variant in a gene where loss of function is a known mechanism of disease. Relevant HPO terms: Renal cell carcinoma, Hemangioblastoma, Multiple pancreatic cysts, Neuroendocrine neoplasm.

Evidence Statements: An investigation of 94 VHL patients without large deletions for intragenic mutations revealed 40 different mutations in 55 unrelated individuals. In all patients with multiple affected family members the missense mutation segregated with the disease. This mutation was found in a VHL type 1 patient (kindred no. 25). Supporting evidence for pathogenicity because of a missense mutation in a gene where missense variants are a common mechanism of disease (ACMG code: PP2).
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: An investigation of 94 VHL patients without large deletions for intragenic mutations revealed 40 different mutations in 55 unrelated individuals. In all patients with multiple affected family members the missense mutation segregated with the disease. Large deletions or intragenic mutations predicted to cause a truncated protein were found in 36 of 53 families without pheochromocytoma (VHL type 1) and 2 of 12 families with pheochromocytoma (VHL type 2). This nonsense mutation was found in a VHL type 1 patient (kindred no. 43). Only moderate support for pathogenicity because protein length changes as a result of stop-loss variant (ACMG code: PM4).

Evidence Statements: An investigation of 94 VHL patients without large deletions for intragenic mutations revealed 40 different mutations in 55 unrelated individuals. In all patients with multiple affected family members the missense mutation segregated with the disease. Missense mutations were found to be more frequent among families affected by pheochromocytoma (VHL type 2) than in those which pheochromocytoma had not occurred (VHL type 1). Most common mutations were missense mutations at codon 167 (codon 238 in publication) and, specifically, substitution of an arginine at codon 167 (codon 238 in publication) was associated with a high risk (62%) of pheochromocytoma. This mutation was found in 3 unrelated VHL patients (kindred no. 70, 95, 116). Two were identified with type 2 phenotype and the third with type 1 phenotype. Mutation also detected in a previous study of a VHL type 2B family of 41 affected patients (family VHL63 in publication) in which 68% had pheochromocytoma, 37% renal cell carcinoma, 68% retinal angiomatosis, and 24% cerebellar hemangioblastomas.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Notes: (Previously cited in Green et al. 1986); Newfoundland kindred. Initial paper showed 38 affected. Current paper confirms 14 people with the mutation. Matched to Green pedigree figure which has patient level data - which one to extract?
Evidence Statements: An investigation of 94 VHL patients without large deletions for intragenic mutations revealed 40 different mutations in 55 unrelated individuals. In all patients with multiple affected family members the missense mutation segregated with the disease. Missense mutations were found to be more frequent among families affected by pheochromocytoma (VHL type 2) than in those which pheochromocytoma had not occurred (VHL type 1). Most common mutations were missense mutations at codon 167 (codon 238 in publication) and, specifically, substitution of an arginine at codon 167 (codon 238 in publication) was associated with a high risk (62%) of pheochromocytoma. This mutation was found in 3 unrelated VHL patients (kindred no. 70, 95, 116). Two were identified with type 2 phenotype and the third with type 1 phenotype. Mutation also detected in a previous study of a VHL type 2B family of 41 affected patients (family VHL63 in publication) in which 68% had pheochromocytoma, 37% renal cell carcinoma, 68% retinal angiomatosis, and 24% cerebellar hemangioblastomas.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: A study of 34 Polish families revealed germline mutations in 30 families. Mutations were not detected in 4 probands fulfilling clinical criteria for von Hippel-Lindau disease (VHLD). This missense mutation was found in a single VHL patient and 2 VHL families with multiple affected individuals. The patient had hemangioblastomas of the central nervous system (family no. 1). A VHL family of 4 affected individuals had one patient with retinal hemangioblastomas, 3 with hemangioblastomas of the central nervous system, and one with renal cell carcinoma (family no. 2). A VHL family of 12 individuals had 10 with retinal hemangioblastomas, 3 with renal cell carcinoma, and 12 with hemangioblastomas of the central nervous system (family no. 3). Supporting evidence of pathogenicity since there is cosegregation with disease in multiple affected family members in a gene definitively known to cause the disease (ACMG code: PP1). HPO terms: hemangioblastoma, retinal hemangioblastoma, renal cell carcinoma.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: This study analyzed screened for VHL and RET mutations in a group of patients taken from the European-American Pheochromocytoma-Paraganglioma and German von Hippel-Lindau Disease Registries. One proband was found to have the above mutation, concurrently with a P81S variant. Family history screening showed the P81S variant was inherited from a healthy father, while the large deletion was de novo. Further familial screening showed the probands son inherited the large VHL deletion and upon inspection displayed manifestations of VHL. Thus, they concluded the P81S variant was non-contributory. Clinical manifestations in this family included: CNS hemangioblastoma, retinal hemangioblastoma, and pancreatic cysts. ACMG evidence codes: 'PVS1' because they observe a deletion variant in a gene where loss of function is a known mechanism of disease, PP4' because the patients' phenotypes or family history are highly specific for a disease with single genetic etiology. Relevant HPO terms: Hemangioblastoma, Retinal hemangioblastoma, Multiple pancreatic cysts.

Evidence Statements: Seven Hungarian families (35 members) with VHL and 37 unrelated patients with apparently sporadic pheochromocytoma had their VHL gene molecularly analyzed. 1 family was found to carry the above mutation; the mutation was molecularly confirmed in 7 family members, two who were asymptomatic. An additional 1 family member had a clinical diagnosis, but was not genetically tested. In the 6 affected family members, clinical manifestations included: renal cell carcinoma in 2, renal cysts in 1, CNS hemangioblastoma in 4, retinal hemangioblastomas in 4, and pheochromocytomas in 3. ACMG evidence codes: 'PP2' because they observe a missense variant in gene where missense variants are common mechanism of disease, 'PP1' based on segregation results, and 'PP4' because the patients phenotypes and family history are highly specific for a disease with single genetic etiology. Relevant HPO terms: Pheochromocytoma, Renal cell carcinoma, Retinal hemangioblastoma, Hemangioblastoma, Multiple renal cysts.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: A novel heterozygous mutation (c.464T>A, p.Val155Glu) was detected in affected family members of a Chinese family. No mutation was detected in unaffected family members. The mutation segregated with the disease phenotype throughout three generations. Case III:1 (the proband) was a 26 year old female whose head CT and MRI exams identified occupying lesions and obstructive hydrocephalus in the cerebellar vermis. Abdominal contrast enhancement CT showed multiple lesions in the liver, pancreas and posterior peritoneum. The cerebellar tumor nodes were removed surgically and a diagnosis of hemangioblastoma was confirmed though histological analysis. The tumors in the proband’s pancreatic tail and retroperitoneal space also were removed subsequently. Histological analysis indicated the tumors to be pancreatic islet cell tumor and phaeochromocytoma, respectively. The probands grandmother (I-1) was 79 years old upon examination and CT and MRI exams identified two occupying cystic nodes in her cerebellar vermis and brain stem space, which later were removed surgically. Histological exam indicated the tumors to be hemangioblastoma.The proband’s 53-year-old father (II-1) was admitted to the hospital for sudden loss of consciousness. Head CT scan revealed cystic lesions with bleeding at left cerebellopontine angle. The tumors were removed surgically and identified as hemangioblastoma in histological examinations. The disease relapsed and the patient was operated on for two more times. Genomic DNA was isolated from venous blood using a Wizard Genomic DNA purifi- cation kit (Takara, China). Oligonucleotide primers to amplify VHL gene exons were designed by software Primer 5.0 according to the NCBI gene database. To verify the mutation identified and to exclude the possibility that the mutation may alter RNA splicing, peripheral blood cells were obtained from the proband and total RNAs were extracted using the Trizol kit (Invitrogen, USA). Complementary cDNAs were made using random primers. VHL cDNA were amplified by RT-PCR Amplified RT- PCR fragments were separated on agarose gels, purified and sequenced. AMCG evidence codes: ’flag for PP4 review’ because the patients phenotype is specific for a mutation in the VHL gene, ‘PP1’ because there is co-segreggation of the variant with VHL disease in the family.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: A novel heterozygous mutation (c.464T>A, p.Val155Glu) was detected in affected family members of a Greek family. No mutation was detected in unaffected family members. Case III:1 (the proband) a female presenting with spinal hemangioblastoma at the age of 12. Other manifestations included retinal hemangioblastoma (13 years), pancreatic cysts (13 years), and cerebellar hemangioblastoma (16 years). The probands father also had features of VHL including multiple spinal hemangioblastomas and retinal hemangioblastomas. Genetic testing confirmed the presence of the above mutation in both proband and father and demonstrated the absence of the mutation in 2 asymptomatic siblings. ACMG evidence codes: 'PP1' because of segregation results, 'PVS1' because they observe a nonsense variant in a gene where loss of function is a known mechanism of disease, and 'PP4' because the patients' phenotypes or family history are highly specific for a disease with single genetic etiology.

Evidence Statements: Two cases of VHL patients presenting with an endolympathic sac tumor are reported. The first patient had no familial history of VHL disease and was 21 years old when he experienced a sudden right hearing loss. Genetic testing revealed the mutation: R113* (c.337C>T). Additional manifestations included: retinal hemangioblastoma, CNS hemangioblastoma, pheochromocytoma, renal cell carcinoma, and pancreatic cysts. After 20 years of radiological surveillance, the size of his endolymphatic sac tumor remained stable. ACMG evidence codes: 'PVS1' because they observe a nonsense variant in a gene where loss of function is a known mechanism of disease, 'PP4' because patient's phenotype or family history is highly specific for a disease with a single genetic etiology.

Evidence Statements: Two VHL syndrome pedigrees were investigated in this study; Family 2 was a a four-generation pedigree containing 24 individuals. In family 2, the proband (F2-II-11), a 45-year-old female patient, presented with paroxysmal hypertension, headache, palpitations and hyperhidrosis in 1985 at the age of 18. US scans showed an isolated mass in the right adrenal gland. Pheochromocytoma was confirmed by histopathological examination. In 2002, the son of the proband (F2-III-9, 9 years old) also presented with paroxysmal hypertension and headache. Biochemical examination indicated increased serum catecholamines, and an isolated mass in the right adrenal gland was confirmed by US and CT scans. Histopathological analysis revealed a right adrenal pheochromocytoma. In 2010, when the patient was 17 years old, pheochromocytoma was confirmed by histopathological examination. Another patient, the niece of the proband (F2-III-4, 33 years old), presented with headache, sustained hypertension, dizzy spells and excess serum catecholamines. Bilateral masses in the adrenal glands were confirmed by US and CT scans when the patient was 28 years old in 2007. Histopathological examination indicated bilateral pheochromocytoma. The 38-year-old father of this patient (F2-II-3, the proband's brother) succumbed to hypertensive intracerebral hemorrhage 21 years prior to this study. Among the members of family 2, three were diagnosed with PCC as the only symptom and no other systematic tumors, including CNS hemangioblastomas, renal cysts or RCC, were identified. A heterozygous nucleotide substitution within exon 3 of the VHL gene, c.482G>A (p.R161Q), was identified in the proband (F2-II-11) and two additional cases (F2-III-4 and F2-III-9) of family 2. Peripheral blood samples were collected for mutation analysis of the RET proto-oncogene and VHL tumor suppressor gene. PCR amplification of all exons and the flanking splice junctions of RET and VHL was performed, followed by direct bidirectional DNA sequencing. One hundred unrelated controls with a similar ethnic background were also included in this study. ACMG evidece codes: ‘PP4’ because the family history is highly specific for a disease with a single genetic etiology, ‘PP1’ because there is co-segreggation of the variant with VHL disease in the family.

Evidence Statements: This paper describes a family suffering from familial pheochromocytoma with seven affected subjects in three generations. Patient patient I,1 (female patient) was found to have bilateral adrenal tumors (pheochromocytomas). She agreed to genetic analysis. Patient II,1 died in childbirth with the symptoms and signs of a hypertensive crisis. Whole body autopsy showed a left adrenal and an extraadrenal pheochromocytoma. The child died 1 day after birth from a cerebral hemorrhage (sex unknown). Patient II,3 (female patient) did not have the familial presentation as confirmed by her family doctor, she agreed to genetic analysis. Patient II,2 (female patient) was found to have bilateral pheochromocytomas. Patient II,4 was a male who presented with bilateral pheochromocytoma. His son, III,1, presented with a right-sided pheochromocytoma. Patient I,2 was a male presenting with right-sided pheochromocytoma. His daughter, II,5, presented with bilateral pheochromocytoma. The family had age of evaluation at 14, 20, 29, 42, 45, 59, and 71 years old, but the patent information was not matched to the ages mentioned. ACMG evidence codes: 'flag for PM2' since the mutation was not found in the single nucleotide polymorphism database, but should have an up to date check preformed, ‘PP1’ because there is co-segreggation of the variant with VHL disease in the family. RET point mutations in genomic DNA of the family members were tested at codons 609,611,618,620, and 634 in exons 10 and 11, respectively. Furthermore, no mutations were found in exon 16 (codon 918). Examination of the vHL gene identified a reported C to G transversion at nucleotide 775 of the published coding sequence. This sequence change was predicted to cause a substitution of a leucine by a valine at codon 259 in the putative vHL protein. This mutation is now reported as L188V (c.562C>G) corresponding to the NM_000551.3 transcript reference. The C775G change segregated with the disease and has not been detected in analysis of more than 400 normal vHL alleles.

Evidence Statements: A 23 year old woman presented with a metastatic pheochromocytoma in the liver and a left adrenal pheochromocytoma. She had no other definitive clinical features of VHL beyond the pheochromocytoma, and was diagnosed with VHL. Germline exonic sequencing of the VHL gene was performed and revealed a c.361(G>C) (p.Asp121His) mutation in her VHL gene. Her father and sister did not possess the variant, and were asymptomatic for VHL features. She had no other family history of VHL disease. Her mother was found to harbour the same germline VHL variant. She was diagnosed with VHL. She presented with multiple asymptomatic VHL-associated lesions, including a spinal hemangioblastoma, bilateral adrenal pheochromocytomas, and two pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors. ACMG evidence codes: PP4: because patient's phenotype or family history is highly specific for a disease with a single genetic etiology, and PP1: Co-segregation with disease in multiple affected family members.

Her mother was found to harbour the same germline VHL variant. She was diagnosed with VHL. She presented with multiple asymptomatic VHL-associated lesions, including a spinal hemangioblastoma, bilateral adrenal pheochromocytomas, and two pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors. ACMG evidence codes: PP4: because patient's phenotype or family history is highly specific for a disease with a single genetic etiology, and PP1: Co-segregation with disease in multiple affected family members.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: A 12 year old female presented with multifocal spinal hemangioblastomas and three hypervascular neoplasms. She was treated with thalidomide, and her last reported age in this paper was 17 (by which time she had shown no additional VHL complications.) Molecular analysis revealed a 4.6kb deletion involving the VHL gene. Her father was clinically diagnosed with VHL and passed away from an inoperable cerebellar hemangioblastoma, and no information about his genotype was given in this paper. ACMG evidence codes: 'PP4' because the patients phenotypes and family history are highly specific for a disease with single genetic etiology.
Warnings: UNKNOWN is not part of genome build GRCh37

Evidence Statements: Nine Chinese index patients were referred for the molecular analysis of VHL based on clinical suspicion. Proband 1 was diagnosed with VHL disease type 1 and was found to have a germline c.481C>T (p.Arg161*) nonsense mutation. They presented with an epididymal cystadenoma at age 40 and a CNS hemangioblastoma and renal cell carcinoma at age 47. Their sister also had VHL disease type 1 and the same mutation, with renal cell carcinoma presenting at age 45. The proband's two daughters did not have the mutation and were asymptomatic. EDTA blood samples were collected for mutation analysis of the VHL gene. Genomic DNA was extracted using the QIAamp blood kit (Qiagen, Hilden, Germany). PCR amplification was performed for genetic analysis of the VHL gene. PCR products were purified by Exo-sapit (GE Healthcare, Uppsala, Sweden) and sequenced using BigDyeDeoxy terminator cycle sequencing (Applied Biosystems, Foster City, CA, USA). ACMG evidence codes: 'PP4' because the patients' phenotypes or family history are highly specific for a disease with a single genetic etiology.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: A cohort of Norwegian pheochromocytoma patients who were operated on at two university hospitals in Norway were analyzed for germline mutations in a number of different genes, including the VHL gene. DNA mutation analyses were performed on blood samples/ paraffin-embedded tissue samples. DN sequencing was performed using Big Dye v3 at 53 °C (Life Technologies, Inc). Patient 1 (case 15 in the paper) had a c.308C>T (p.Pro103Leu) mutation in the VHL gene. They presented with a pheochromocytoma and their age at the time of surgery was 48 years old, and they had no family history of neuroendocrine tumors. Their DNA was analyzed from a blood sample. ACMG evidence codes: none.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: Families with VHL disease type 2A were were evaluated for mutations in the VHL gene. In four families, three different coding sequence substitutions causing a 15 amino-acid extension from the original stop codon of the VHL gene were described. Genomic DNA was extracted from peripheral blood lymphocytes using standard procedures. Sequence analysis consisted of polymerase chain reaction (PCR) amplification and automated fluorescence sequencing of all three VHL exons. Patient 1 (family 1), female, presented with a pheochromocytoma at age 11, a pheochromocytoma at age 20, bilateral retinal hemangioblastoma at age 20, and a pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor at age 20. She had a family history of early onset pheochromocytoma. She was found to have a substitution mutation in the VHL gene causing a loss of the stop codon, and an extension of 14 amino acids on the C-terminal end of the protein (c.641G>T (p.*241Lext*14). This mutation is noted as p.*241Lext*15 in the paper due to a difference in nomenclature.) Her mother was found to have the same mutation. Her mother had two pheochromocytomas at age 12, and was found to have bilateral retinal hemangioblastomas at age 40. Her brother was found to have a pheochromocytoma at age 13, but was not sequenced. Her maternal gradnfather was noted to have had liver cancer at 72, her great grandfather had unpecified cancer, and her great aunt had Hodgkin's lymphoma at age 38. A second patient (patient 2) from an independent family was found to have the same mutation as patient 1. Patient 2 was also female and presented with bilateral retinal hemangioblastomas. Her last recorded age was 38 years old, and no age of diagnosis was provided. ACMG evidence codes: 'PP1'- Cosegregation with disease in multiple affected family members in a gene definitively known to cause the disease, and 'PP4'- patients' phenotypes or family history are highly specific for a disease with a single genetic etiology.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: A 2.75 year old patient (32 month-old girl) presented with a pheochromocytoma. Genetic sequencing revealed a c.491A>G (p.Gln164Arg) heterozygous germline mutation in exon 3 of the VHL gene. Sequencing of her mother, father, a sibling, and her paternal grandparents revealed that the mutation was present only in her father, and was de-novo in her father. Upon screening, her father (a 31 year old male) presented with a retinal angioma, an adenoma of right adrenal gland, a right-sided renal cyst, an epidydymal cyst, a contrast-enhancing lesion in the pancreas, and bilateral pheochromocytomas. ACMG evidence codes: 'PP1'- Cosegregation with disease in multiple affected family members in a gene definitively known to cause the disease, and 'PP4'- patients' phenotypes or family history are highly specific for a disease with a single genetic etiology.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: A 2.75 year old patient (32 month-old girl) presented with a pheochromocytoma. Genetic sequencing revealed a c.491A>G (p.Gln164Arg) heterozygous germline mutation in exon 3 of the VHL gene. Sequencing of her mother, father, a sibling, and her paternal grandparents revealed that the mutation was present only in her father, and was de-novo in her father. Upon screening, her father (a 31 year old male) presented with a retinal angioma, an adenoma of right adrenal gland, a right-sided renal cyst, an epidydymal cyst, a contrast-enhancing lesion in the pancreas, and bilateral pheochromocytomas. ACMG evidence codes: 'PP1'- Cosegregation with disease in multiple affected family members in a gene definitively known to cause the disease, and 'PP4'- patients' phenotypes or family history are highly specific for a disease with a single genetic etiology.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: A 32 year old woman presented with a spinal hemangioblastoma (located in the cauda equina) and pancreatic cysts. She was diagnosed with VHL genetically and clinically, and was found to have a c.280G>T (p.Glu94*) mutation in her VHL gene. Her mother also had a history of spinal hemangioblastoma (located in the thoracic cord). There was no mention of genetic testing performed on her mother in this paper. 'PP4'- patients' phenotypes or family history are highly specific for a disease with a single genetic etiology.

Evidence Statements: Thirty-five unrelated patients suspected of having von Hippel-Lindau disease were analyzed and 32 VHL gene variants were found in 35 patients. An association of clear cell renal carcinoma development with a relatively high loss of structural stability in VHL protein missense mutations was discovered. This nonsense mutation was found in a patient with retinal hemangioblastoma, cerebellar hemangioblastoma, and pancreatic cysts (patient no. F3). Patient has family history of paragangliomas, epididymial cysts, and clear cell renal carcinoma. The nucleotide change was not provided in the paper. This study contains very strong evidence for pathogenicity in the form of a nonsense mutation in a gene where loss-of-function is a known mechanism of disease (ACMG code: PVS1). HPO terms: retinal hemangioblastoma, hemangioblastoma, multiple pancreatic cysts.

Evidence Statements: Thirty-five unrelated patients suspected of having von Hippel-Lindau disease were analyzed and 32 VHL gene variants were found in 35 patients. An association of clear cell renal carcinoma development with a relatively high loss of structural stability in VHL protein missense mutations was discovered. VGL gene rearrangements were found in 8 patients. One patient with a VHL rearangement, had an age of onset of 30 years old and presented with Cerebellar Haemangioblastoma, billateral phaeochromocytoma and retinal hemangioblastomas. There was also a family history of broad ligament cysts and pancreatic cysts. In the next patient with a VHL rearrangement, they had an age of onset at 23 years old and presented with retinal hemangioblastomas, renal cyst, cerebellar  hemangioblastoma, unilateral phaeochromocytoma, billateral CCRC. The third patient mentioned in this paper with a chromosomal rearrangement had an age of onset at 58 years old and presented with pacreatic cyst, cerebellar hemangioblastomas, billateral CCRC, renal cyst. Their family history also included instances of retinal hemangioblastomas. The fourth patient with a VHL rearrangement had an age of onset of 39 years old and presented with cerebellar hemangioblastomas, unilateral phaeochromocytoma, renal cyst, pancreatic cyst. The 5th pathient with a VHL rearrangement had an age of onset of 30 years old and presented with cerebellar hemangioblastoma, endolymphatic sac tumor, The 6th patent has an age of onset of 12 years old and presented with cerebellar hemangioblastomas, unilateral CCRC, renal cyst, pancreatic cyst,  Epydidimal cysts. The 7th patient with a VHL rearrangement had an age of onset of 54 and presented with spinal hemangioblastomas, bilateral CCRC, Paraganglioma. The 8th patient had an age of onset of 44 years old and presented with cerebellar hemangioblastomas, Unilateral CCRC (patients F22, F28, F58, F39, F27, F45, F55, F58 respectivly). These rearrangements were discovered by a southern blot positive test. Using three different restriction enzymes, they found the eight families that had presented gross rearrangements along the VHL gene. A detailed map of the deleted segments could not be performed since all restriction assays were insufficient to define the VHL region that was lost. ACMG evidence codes:  "flag for PP4" because patients phenotype is highly specific for the disease.

Evidence Statements: Germline mutations were found in twenty VHL probands and their families, of whom 17 presented with a family history (15 from Brazil, one from Portugal, and one from Ecuador) . An intronic variant,  c.340+7G>A,(reported as IVS1+7G>A in the paper) was found in 2 affected family members that both presented with with hemangioblastomas of the CNS. They were able to analyse the germline mutation linkage to disease in this family. The pathogenic nature of the variant was not confirmed at the mRNA level; however, the fact that this alteration was not detected in one unaffected first degree relative (after clinical and radiological screening) suggests that it may be associated with the disease. Additionally, the reported novel mutation were not represented in 120 alleles from normal subjects in the Brazilian population suggesting that these base changes are not common polymorphisms. This variant was reported as a Splicing defect. ACMG codes: none.

Evidence Statements: Germline mutations were found in 20 Brazilian, VHL probands and their families. The mutation, H115Pfs*44 (c.344delA), was found in a VHL type 1 family of 3 affected individuals (VHL family 9). One had hemangioblastomas of the central nervous system, one with retinal angiomas, and one with renal carcinoma. Within this family a second mutation was also discovered in the VHL gene, P61= (183C>G), which was assumed to not be deleterious. ACMG codes as follows: A frameshift mutation in a gene where loss-of-function is a known mechanism of disease (PVS1). Cosegregation with disease in multiple affected family members in a gene definitively known to cause the disease (PP1). HPO terms: hemangioblastoma, retinal hemangioblastoma, renal cell carcinoma.

Evidence Statements: Germline mutations were found in 20 Brazilian, VHL probands and their families. A partial deletion of VHL was found in a family of 10 affected individuals. All ten family members had CNS hemangioblastoma, 1 had retinal angiomas and 5 also had renal carcinoma (VHL family 17). Within this family a second mutation was also discovered in the VHL gene:P61= (183C>G), which was assumed to not be deleterious. A partial deletion was also discovered in another family (family 18) who had 5 affected individuals, 2 of which had CNS hemangioblastoma, 1 had retinal angioma, and others had Pancreatic cystadenoma. A third family was discovered to have a partial deletion of VHL (family 19) who had 3 affected members, who all had CNS hemangioblastomas. Germline VHL gene mutations were detected using a combination of direct sequencing and quantitative Southern blotting. ACMG codes: "flag for PP1" because there is co-segregation with multiple family mamber and "flag for PP4" because patients phenotype is highly specific for the disease.

Evidence Statements: Germline mutations were found in 20 Brazilian, VHL probands and their families. A complete deletion of VHL was found in a family of 6 affected individuals. Four of the family members had CNS hemangioblastoma, 3 had renal carcinoma, and 1 had pancreatic carcinoma (VHL family 20). Germline VHL gene mutations were detected using a combination of direct sequencing and quantitative Southern blotting. Complete deletion of the VHL gene produced a single 9.7 kb band with 50% relative intensity after normalisation, which was confirmed by densitometry of the bands. ACMG codes: "flag for PP1" because there is co-segregation with multiple family mamber and "flag for PP4" because patients phenotype is highly specific for the disease.

Notes: Patient 3, Iraqi; brain cancer (suspected hemangioblastoma); eye disease (suspected retinal capillary hemangioma)
Evidence Statements: This paper reports an Iraqi family with VHL. Two family members presented to a New Zealand Genetics service because of a family history of VHL. Genetic screening identified a single family member with the above VHL mutation. More specifically, this mutation is believed to cause the following protein change: p.F76Hfs*57. This patient presented with CNS hemangioblastoma, renal cell carcinoma, retinal hemangioblastoma, and renal cysts. Family history showed 4 other family members who had presumed VHL, but died before testing could be performed. Manifestations in these members included: renal cell carcinoma, CNS hemangioblastoma, and retinal hemangioblastoma. Interestingly, a single family member was found to be an obligate heterozygote from the pedigree, but did not show VHL-related manifestations. This member is believed to be non-penetrant. ACMG evidence codes: 'PVS1' because they observe a frameshift variant in a gene where loss of function is a known mechanism of disease, 'PP4' because the patient's phenotype or family history is highly specific for a disease with a single genetic etiology. Relevant HPO terms: Renal cell carcinoma, Hemangioblastoma, Retinal hemangioblastoma, Multiple renal cysts.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: A report of a duplication mutation in a 5-generation Chinese family. Of the 38 family members analyzed only 10 members were identified with this mutation. Five family members with the duplication mutation were asymptomatic for manifestations of VHL disease. Specifically, the above mutation causes the following protein change: p.Gly114Serfs*50. Three family members with hemangioblastomas of the central nervous system passed away before 40 years of age and before testing could be conducted. Among the 5 living patients, 3 had renal cysts, one had renal cell carcinoma, 2 had central nervous system hemangioblastoma, one had retinal hemangioblastomas, and one was diagnosed with glioblastoma. The presence of 5 asymptomatic is surprising, but we know that at least one patient refused asymptomatic screening so it may be an overestimate of asymptomatic carriers. ACMG codes as follows: A frameshift variant in a gene where loss-of-function is a known mechanism of disease (PVS1). Cosegregation with disease in multiple affected family members in a gene definitively known to cause the disease (PP1). Patient's phenotypes or family history are highly specific for a disease with single genetic etiology (PP4). Relevant HPO terms: Hemangioblastoma, Renal cell carcinoma, Retinal hemangioblastoma, Multiple renal cysts.
Transcript_description: Homo sapiens von Hippel-Lindau tumor suppressor (VHL), transcript variant 1, mRNA

Evidence Statements: Of 65 VHL families from central Europe, 53 were identified with germline mutations. This splice mutation was found in a Croatian, VHL type 1 family of 3. Each individual had retinal angiomas, one had hemangioblastomas of the central nervous system, one had renal cell carcinoma, and one had pancreatic cysts (family VHL 7). This study contains very strong evidence of pathogenicity in the form of a canonical +2 splice site variant in a gene where loss-of-function is a known mechanism of disease (ACMG code: PVS1).

Evidence Statements: Germline mutations were found in 20 Brazilian VHL probands and their families. The delPhe76 mutation was found in a VHL type 1 family of 5 affected individuals (VHL family 1). Of the 5 effected family members four patients had hemangioblastomas of the central nervous system and 2 had renal carcinoma.I n family 1 was genetic testing performed in a non-symptomatic boy, since no relatives were alive for testing. Although many members of this family had already presented with HB, the diagnosis of VHL was confirmed after necropsy of the proband’s father, who died at 37 years from complications following emergency surgery for cerebellar HB. The necropsy showed many occult lesions related to VHL, including RC, multiple pancreatic and renal cysts, and cystadenoma of the epididymis. ACMG codes as follows: Protein length changes as a result of a in-frame deletion in a nonrepeat region (PM4).

Evidence Statements: The authors comprehensively examined the VHL status in tissue samples from 115 patients undergoing nephrectomy. Mutation was detected using denaturing high-pressure liquid chromatography and DNA sequencing. Loss of heterozygosity analysis, promotor methylation analysis and detection of copy number changes in VHL gene was also performed. In the 2 tumor samples from patients with familial VHL disease, C77fsX131(c.228_229insC) mutation was detected. Loss of heterozygosity was seenin both of the familial VHL cases.
